body:
> 1. Allow nested arrays

üëç 

> 2. Introduce an extends key

üëç but a few thoughts:

a. I don't really support reintroducing string-style, but if we decide to do so, it would be nice to support doing so on the outer layer as well to avoid confusion:
```js
export default ["js/recommended"];
```

b. how to merge the `files`:

```js
import js from "@eslint/js";

export default [
    {
        plugins: {
            js
        },
        files: ["**/*.js"],
        extends: ["js/recommended"],
        rules: {
            "prefer-const": "off"
        }
    }
];
```

what if the `js/recommended` has `files` or `ignores`?

c. Whether the use of keys other than `files/ignores/extends` should be restricted?
* it could make merging easier (I guess).
* enforce the same functionality to be implemented in the same way - the above example can be written to:
```
export default [
    {
        files: ["**/*.js"],
        extends: ["js/recommended", {plugins: {js}, rules: {"prefer-const": "off"}}],
    }
];
```

One thing to consider with string references that could lead to weirdness.

What happens if the user does this:

```js
import ts from 'typescript-eslint';

export default [
  {
    plugins: { ts },
    extends: ['ts/recommended'],
  },
];
```

What would the resulting config be?

As a user I might expect that for example the rule `ts/no-explicit-any` is turned on because they've referenced the plugin and the config via the `ts` namespace. However that wouldn't be the case - instead the rule would be turned on as `@typescript-eslint/no-explicit-any` (as it is defined in the config).

OTOH the non-string code:
```js
import ts from 'typescript-eslint';

export default [
  {
    plugins: { ts },
    extends: [ts.configs.recommended],
  },
];
```

Is (IMO) less ambiguous what the result would be.

I was reading through https://github.com/eslint/eslint/discussions/16960 because we recently migrated our monorepo to ESLint v9 and I ran into a few trouble spots. One of my mistakes gave me a possible idea for `extends`.

This is what I tried:

```ts
export default tseslint.config({
  files: ["**/*.ts"],
  extends: [...storybookPlugin.configs["flat/recommended"]],
});
```

Unfortunately `tseslint.config` overwrites each shared config's `files`, causing rules to apply too widely:

```ts
export default [
  {
    name: "storybook:recommended:stories-rules",
    files: ["**/*.ts"],
  },
];
```

I could imagine an ESLint `extends` normalizing to this instead, where files must match **any** pattern in **every** array:

```ts
export default [
  {
    name: "storybook:recommended:stories-rules",
    files: [["**/*.ts"], ["**/*.stories.*", "**/*.story.*"]],
  },
];
```

Between this and allowing nested configs, I think you could solve most of the pain points people are having right now.

It's worth noting `files` already supports `string[][]`, but its utility is limited because the any/all logic is reversed. It's currently slated for removal in v10 (https://github.com/eslint/eslint/issues/18966), and maybe that makes room for something like this.

@bradzacher @aladdin-add I think this is all good feedback, but it's better to wait for an RFC to discuss things in this much detail. I think there are so serious advantages to allowing named string configs, and it's difficult to articulate them in this format without extensive examples and explanations.

What I'm looking for here is "yes we like this general idea" or "no we don't like this general idea."

@eslint/eslint-team could use some opinions here.
